Introduction:

The ongoing discussion about who should pay for university tuition fees has sparked various viewpoints. Recently, an article suggested that all students should contribute, regardless of their family's financial situation.

My Opinion:

I disagree with this notion. It's unfair to expect equal payments from all students when families have different financial capabilities. This approach creates inequality in accessing education.

Argument 1:

Making all students pay overlooks the societal benefits of accessible education. It might discourage talented individuals from pursuing higher education, slowing down societal progress and innovation.

Argument 2:

Furthermore, education benefits society as a whole. By putting the entire financial burden on students and families, we neglect investing in our collective future.

Conclusion:

The idea of universal payment for higher education ignores real-world economic differences and the broader advantages of accessible education. Instead, we should focus on policies that ensure everyone has equal opportunities for education, regardless of financial constraints.

